:::summary
Joan of Arc (c. 1412–1431) was a French peasant girl who, claiming divine guidance from saints and angels, rallied the French army, secured the coronation of King Charles VII, and turned the tide of the Hundred Years' War against England. Captured, tried for heresy, and burned at the stake at age nineteen, she was rehabilitated by the Church and canonized as a saint in 1920 — one of the most extraordinary and beloved figures in all of Christian history.
:::

